#RULES FOR JAVA STYLE#
#packages start with lowercase
#classes start with Uppercase
#methods start with lowercase
#Constants are ALL uppercase
#variable names are lowercase
###########################
##JAVA PRIMITIVE TYPES
#byte - 8 bit number
#short - 16 bit number
#integer - 32 bit number
#long - 64 bit number
#float - 32 bit float
#double - 64 bit float
#boolean - T/F
#char - characters
############################
#BigDecimal is a class alternative to the double and float types
#pass strings instead of numbers for precision with Bigdecimal
#casting - java will automatically cast form less info to more
#byte<short<char<int<long<float<double
#long to float can lose info (float is lower bits but includes other chars)
#casting is (float)integer or whatever
#you have to cast right to left, otherwise you can just declare
#even without info loss you need to cast
################################################################
#going left to right, java casts for you
#this can lead to errors
#########################################
#arrays are declared with []
#int x[] = new int[10];
#or intx[] = {0,10,2,34,8}
#size of arrays cannot be changed
#multidimensional arrays: arrays of arrays
###################
#METHODS#
#public class x
#public x (declarations) #THIS IS CONSTRUCTOR
#public void foobar(parameters)
#put method outside of main, but call the method in main
############################
#BUBBLE SORT ALGORITHM#
#compares current number and previous number and if the second number is lower, swap them
#does this for every number compared to every other number (a1,a2,a3,b1,b2,b3)
#performance is N^2
#O notation is measure of performance
